{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"68bdc7dd-be21-4acd-a579-bfef83c4be0b","content":"Here's what breaks in each snippet for .NET 10:\n\n---\n\n**Form1.cs** — `ContextMenu`/`MenuItem` are **removed** in .NET 10 (obsolete since .NET 7). Replace with:\n\n```csharp\nvar menu = new ContextMenuStrip();\nmenu.Items.Add(new ToolStripMenuItem(\"Open\", image: null, OnOpen));\n```\n\nNote: the handler signature stays `EventHandler` but the sender is now `ToolStripMenuItem`.\n\n---\n\n**ImageProcessor.cs** — `new Bitmap(path)` no longer throws `OutOfMemoryException` for invalid/corrupt images (a long-standing GDI+ quirk). .NET 10 throws `ArgumentException` instead, so your catch won't fire:\n\n```csharp\ncatch (ArgumentException ex)\n{\n    logger.LogError(ex, \"Invalid image format\");\n}\n```\n\nOr catch both if you also target older runtimes.\n\n---\n\n**MainWindow.xaml** — WPF in .NET 10 **throws at runtime** for unresolved `DynamicResource` keys instead of silently returning null. `MissingKey` will crash unless you define it or add a fallback:\n\n```xml\n<TextBlock Text=\"{DynamicResource MissingKey, FallbackValue='(none)'}\" />\n```\n\nOr add the key to a resource dictionary.\n\nThe empty `<Grid.ColumnDefinitions/>` and `<Grid.RowDefinitions/>` are harmless but unnecessary — remove them to avoid confusion.\n\n---\n\n**Additional items you mentioned:**\n\n- **StatusStrip** — .NET 10 changes the default `RenderMode`. If you depend on the classic system-drawn look, explicitly set `RenderMode = ToolStripRenderMode.System`.\n- **TreeView CheckBoxes** — .NET 10 changes how checkbox state propagation works. Verify your `AfterCheck` handlers still behave correctly, especially for parent/child state syncing.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6d49dfa7-b148-4054-9a54-7b6ba38bf811","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating a .NET 9 Windows desktop app to .NET 10. Let me analyze each code snippet for known breaking changes in .NET 10.\n\n