ET 10 changed the behavior—it now throws `ArgumentException` instead of `OutOfMemoryException` when given an invalid image format. I should also note that the legacy `ContextMenu` and `MenuItem` types are gone, so I need to migrate to `ContextMenuStrip` and `ToolStripMenuItem` with the updated event handler patterns. In recent .NET versions, System.Drawing changed how it reports errors—the old GDI+ behavior of throwing `OutOfMemoryException` for corrupt images was replaced with more appropriate exception types, so that catch block would miss the actual error now.\n\nFor the XAML, empty `Grid.ColumnDefinitions` and `Grid.RowDefinitions` might be handled differently in .NET 10, and `DynamicResource` references to missing keys could now throw exceptions at runtime instead of silently failing like they used to.\n\nLooking at the specific issues: `ContextMenu` and `MenuItem` are gone in .NET 10, so I need to switch those to `ContextMenuStrip` and `ToolStripMenuItem`. The `Bitmap` constructor now throws `ArgumentException` instead of `OutOfMemoryException` for invalid images. The missing `DynamicResource` key needs either the resource defined or a fallback value specified. There are also potential rendering and behavior changes with `StatusStrip` and `TreeView` checkboxes that might need attention. DefinitionsRowDefinitions` may also behave differently. The default `RenderMode` for `StatusStrip` has changed in .NET 10, which could affect how controls render visually. There's also a known behavior change with `TreeView` checkbox state management. I should be careful about my confidence level here—while the `ContextMenu`/`MenuItem` removal is high confidence based on the progression of .NET changes, some of these other details depend on specifics that may have shifted during .NET 10's development.","outputTokens":2989,"requestId":"B820:270DE0:162CF75:18E41A3:69FD380E"},"id":"ae21e4e4-c08d-4bed-beb4-4b8ac279fd57","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:11:38.439Z","parentId":"7ca08f88-eb